Business Experiments

Topics Covered

  1. Difference between experimental and observational data

  2. Understand the difference between a tactical experiment designed to inform a business decision and an experiment designed to test a scientific theory.

  3. The “big three” of causality

  4. Give examples of how experiments can be used to inform specific business decisions.

What is a Business Experiment?

A business experiment is merely an experiment whose purpose is to inform a business decision.

In contrast, other disciplines (medicine, psychology, biology) develop theories and then use experiments to test the theory.

Engineers usually have well-specified physical models, subjects that are physical entities that respond predictably and prediction methods have small errors.

In business well specified models are the exceptions, subjects are often human (who can respond in two different ways to the same stimulus!) and prediction methods have large errors.

Here are some famous predictions of consumer behavior:

1.”The Iphone is the most expensive phone in the world, and it doesn’t appeal to business customers because it doesn’t have a keyboard, which makes it not a very good e-mail machine”–Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer (2007)

2.”People have told us over and over and over again, they don’t want to rent their music…they don’t want subscriptions”–Apple CEO Steve Jobs (2003)

  1. “Television won’t be able to hold on to any market it captures after the first six months. People will soon get tired of staring at a plywood box every night”–Attributed to 20th Century Fox studio head Darryl F. Zanuck (1946)

You may have heard of “A/B” testing which is the language often used to describe a website test. But experimentation in Business goes way beyond web experiments and we will look at examples of those in a minute. Here are some examples.

  1. When Kohl’s was considering adding a new product category, furniture, many executives were tremendously enthusiastic, anticipating significant additional revenue. A test at 70 stores over six months, however, showed a net decrease in revenue. Products that now had less floor space (to make room for the furniture) experienced a drop in sales, and Kohl’s was actually losing customers overall. Those negative results were a huge disappointment for those who had advocated for the initiative, but the program was nevertheless scrapped. The Kohl’s example highlights the fact that experiments are often needed to perform objective assessments of initiatives backed by people with organizational clout.

  2. At Publix Super Markets, a chain in the southeastern United States, virtually all large retail projects, especially those requiring considerable capital expenditures, must undergo formal experiments to receive a green light. Proposals go through a filtering process in which the first step is for finance to perform an analysis to determine if an experiment is worth conducting.

  3. The financial services company Capital One has long used rigorous experiments to test even the most seemingly trivial changes. Through randomized field trials, for instance, the company might test the color of the envelopes used for product offers by sending out two batches (one in the test color and the other in white) to determine any differences in response.

  4. Cracker Barrel Old Country Store, the Southern-themed restaurant chain, conducted an experiment to determine whether it should switch from incandescent to LED lights at its restaurants.

Four Steps for a Simple Experiment

  1. Randomly divide the subjects (e.g. customers) into groups.

  2. Expose each group to a different treatment.

  3. Measure a response for each group.

  4. Compare group responses to determine which treatment is better.

Experiments are a systematic way to avoid lurking variables and are the gold standard for causal inference.

Most Expeirments Fail

The purpose of an experiment is to test an idea, not provide something. The goal is to create a process where bad ideas fail quickly.

“If you have to kiss a lot of frogs to find a prince, find more frogs and kiss them faster and faster”–Mike Moran, Do it Wrong Quickly (2007)

“If you want to increase your success rate, double your failure rate”–Thomas J. Watson

“I have not failed, I’ve just found 10,000 ways that didn’t work.”–Thomas Edison

The Big Three of Causality

  1. When X changed, Y also changed. If X changes and Y doesn’t change, then we cannot assert that X causes Y.

  2. X happened before Y. If X happens after Y then X cannot cause Y.

  3. Nothing else besides X changed systematically.

A/B Web Test Examples

Here is an example where the control version, or the current version of the website offered a discount off a future purchase.

The test removed the incentive.

The test page performed 40% better than the control.

Website testing is so popular that nearly every large website has an ongoing testing program, including Miami University.

Here is awebsite full of examples of A/B tests.

To get statistically sound results in a website test you need a lot of traffic, we will discuss how to make some preliminary calculations on this later in the course.

There are many things you can measure on a website test to determine success. This measure is often referred to as the Key Product Indicator (KPI).

Examples include:

  • number of sign ups
  • sales per session
  • Click through rate
  • provide email address

The results of these tests are reported as significant or not and if the test proved to be significant, then the measure used to convey how much better one version was than the other is lift. A percent improvement of one over the other.
